Meta-Analytic Structural Equation Modeling

Mike Cheung

8-10 Feb 2023 (Day 2, Session 2)

Addressing heterogeneity in MASEM

  • Heterogeneity is an essential issue in meta-analysis. When there is a large amount of heterogeneity, the average becomes less important.
  • We will introduce how to address heterogeneity in MASEM.

Subgroup analysis

  • When the assumption of the common correlation matrix is not tenable, we may try two alternative approaches: A subgroup analysis or a random-effects model
  • Subgroup analysis: try to group studies according to the study characteristics into relatively homogeneous subgroups (Cheung & Chan, 2005; Jak & Cheung, 2018)1, 2
    • Pros: Similar to conventional meta-regression by using study characteristics as the moderators;
    • Cons: Only categorical moderators are allowed; fewer studies are in each group.

Random-effects TSSEM

  • The fixed-effects TSSEM has been extended to a random-effects model (Cheung, 2014), which is mathematically the same as the random-effects GLS proposed by Becker (1992).
  • There are several pros and cons of applying a random-effects model:
    • Pros: Treating differences across studies as random effects;
    • Cons: Difficult to explain study differences by using study characteristics as the moderators.
  • Stage 1 analysis:
    • Multivariate random-effects model is used to synthesize correlation matrices;
  • Stage 2 analysis:
    • Similar to the fixed-effects TSSEM, we use the WLS estimation to fit structural equation models on the average correlation matrix.

A conceptual overview of TSSEM

Jak and Cheung (2020, Figure 1)

Random-effects TSSEM: Stage 1 analysis (1)

  • A multivariate meta-analysis is used to synthesize the correlation matrices
    • \(\boldsymbol{r}_i = \boldsymbol{\rho}_\mathrm{R} + \boldsymbol{u}_i + \boldsymbol{e}_i\),
    • where \(\mathrm{Var}(\boldsymbol{e}_i)=V_i\) is the known sampling covariance matrix and \(\mathrm{Var}(\boldsymbol{u}_i)=T^2\) is the heterogeneity covariance matrix that has to be estimated.
  • The SEM-based multivariate meta-analysis is used to obtain the average correlation matrix \(R_\mathrm{R}\) and its asymptotic sampling covariance matrix \(V_\mathrm{R}\).
  • The sampling covariance matrix of the correlations can be obtained by the following R code.
library(metaSEM)

## Sample correlation matrix
R <- matrix(c(1, .3, .4,
              .3, 1, .5,
              .4, .5, 1), nrow=3, ncol=3,
            dimnames = list(c("x1", "x2", "x3"), c("x1", "x2", "x3")))
R
##     x1  x2  x3
## x1 1.0 0.3 0.4
## x2 0.3 1.0 0.5
## x3 0.4 0.5 1.0
vechs(R)
## [1] 0.3 0.4 0.5
## Compute the sampling covariance matrix of the correlations with n=100
asyCov(R, n=100)
##          x2_x1    x3_x1    x3_x2
## x2_x1 0.008281 0.003450 0.002265
## x3_x1 0.003450 0.007056 0.001270
## x3_x2 0.002265 0.001270 0.005625

Random-effects TSSEM: Stage 1 analysis (2)

  • \(I^2\), the percentage of between-study variance to the total variance, can be calculated for each correlation coefficient to indicate the degree of heterogeneity.
  • Notes on the heterogeneity matrix (\(T^2\)) in stage 1 analysis:
    • The no. of effect sizes is usually much larger in MASEM than in conventional multivariate meta-analysis.
    • For example, it is uncommon to have \(p=5\) variables in a MASEM. There will be \(5 \times (5-1)/2=10\) effect sizes and \(10 \times (10+1)/2=55\) elements in \(T^2\).
    • There may not be enough studies to estimate the full \(T^2\).
    • If this happens, we may use a diagonal matrix for \(T^2\) (RE.type="Diag").

Random-effects TSSEM: Stage 2 analysis

  • Suppose the proposed correlation structure is \(\rho_\mathrm{R}(\theta)=\mathrm{vechs}(P_\mathrm{R}(\theta))\), the discrepancy function is
    • \(F_\mathrm{WLS}(\theta) = (r_\mathrm{R} - \rho_\mathrm{R}(\theta))^\mathrm{T} V_\mathrm{R}^{-1} (r_\mathrm{R} - \rho_\mathrm{R}(\theta))\)
    • The model is similar to that for the fixed-effects TSSEM.
  • Notes on the heterogeneity matrix (\(T^2\)) in stage 2 analysis:
    • \(T^2\) is not directly involved in the above fit function;
    • As \(V_\mathrm{R}\) is estimated after controlling for the random effects \(T^2\), \(V_\mathrm{R}\) has already been taken the random effects into account;
    • \(V_\mathrm{R}\) is usually larger than \(V_\mathrm{F}\). Thus, the SEs in the random-effects model are generally larger than those in the fixed-effects model.

OSMASEM approach

  • The current approaches, except the Bayesian approach, do not handle continuous moderators properly.
  • Jak and Cheung (2020) proposed a one-stage MASEM approach that handles categorical and continuous moderators in MASEM.

Conceptual model

OSMASEM approach with a moderator

  • Suppose we want to use Lag to predict the path coefficient w2w. The model is
    • \(\beta_{w2w} = w2w + w2w_1*Lag\), where w2w is the path coefficient when Lag=0 and w2w_1 is the change when Lag increases one unit.
    • \(\beta_{w2s} = w2s + w2s_1*Lag\)
    • \(\beta_{s2w} = s2w + s2w_1*Lag\)
    • \(\beta_{s2s} = s2s + s2s_1*Lag\)

Jak and Cheung (2020)

Correction for unreliability

  • The observed correlation coefficients are usually smaller than the actual correlations without measurement error.
  • We may correct the measurement error by:
    • \(r_{corrected} = \frac{r_{xy}}{\sqrt{r_{xx'}{r_{yy'}}}}\), where \(r_{corrected}\) is the corrected correlation, \(r_{xy}\) is the observed correlation, \(r_{xx'}\) and \(r_{yy'}\) are the reliability coefficients of \(x\) and \(y\), respectively.
  • There is some controversy over whether it is necessary to correct for attenuation and statistical artifacts.
    • Rosenthal (1991)3 criticized the use of a correction for attenuation because the corrected values are not as useful as the uncorrected values in realistic settings.
    • Other researchers (e.g., Schmidt and Hunter, 2015)4 argued for correcting for attenuation before combining the correlation matrices.
  • MASEM:
    • Michel et al. (2011)5 suggested that substantive model conclusions in the psychological literature are generally unaffected by study artifacts and related statistical corrections.
    • As their conclusions are based on real examples rather than computer simulations, further research may address the effects of unreliability in MASEM.

Examples and applications

Example 1: A Five-Factor model

  • This example illustrates how to apply MASEM to models with latent variables.
  • Digman (1997)6 reported 14 correlation matrices among the five-factor model. He argued that the Big Five personality were not independent; these factors were loaded on two independent factors:
    • Alpha factor (general personality of socialization): Agreeableness (A), conscientiousness (C), and emotional stability (ES; the reverse of neuroticism)
    • Beta factor (personal growth): extraversion (E) and intellect (I)

The dataset

  • The dataset is available in the metaSEM package as Digman97 (see ?Digman97 after loading the metaSEM package).
  • To illustrate how to prepare data for MASEM, I have converted it to Excel format.
  • The first sheet (Info) includes the study characteristics, whereas the other sheets (Study 1 to Study 14) store the correlation matrices.

Reading the Excel file into R

## Load the library for MASEM

Proposed model in lavaan

  • Most users find it easier to specify the models in lavaan syntax.
    • f =~ x1 + x2 + x3: the latent factor f is measured by x1, x2, and x3.
    • y ~ x1 + x2: y regresses on x1 and x2 or y is modeled by x1 and x2.
    • x1 ~~ x2: x1 and x2 are correlated.
## Specify the model with default labels
model1 <- "## Factor loadings
           ## Alpha is measured by A, C, and ES
           Alpha =~ A + C + ES
           ## Beta is measured by E and I
           Beta =~ E + I
           ## Factor correlation between Alpha and Beta
           Alpha ~~ Beta"

## Display the model
## See ?plot.character for the help page
plot(model1, color="yellow")

Proposed model in RAM specification

  • The metaSEM package uses the Reticular Action Model (RAM) specification. We may convert the lavaan model to RAM specification with the lavaan2RAM() function.
  • Although we do not need to specify models in RAM, it is helpful to check the RAM specification to ensure that we fit the correct model.
  • An A matrix specifies the direct paths (single arrows) among the variables. Columns represent independent variables (IVs), whereas rows represent dependent variables (DVs).
    • The default label is DVonIV or ROWonCOLUMN.
    • \(A = \left[ {\begin{array}{c|ccccccc} & A & C & ES & E& I & Alpha & Beta \\ \hline A& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& AonAlpha& 0&\\ C& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& ConAlpha& 0&\\ ES& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& ESonAlpha& 0&\\ E& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& EonBeta& \\ I& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& IonBeta& \\ Alpha& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& \\ Beta& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& \\ \end{array} } \right]\)
  • An S matrix specifies the symmetric paths (double arrows) among the variables. The diagonals represent the variances, whereas the off-diagonals represent the covariances.
    • Since we are analyzing correlation matrices, the variances of the independent variables are fixed at 1.
    • \(S = \left[ {\begin{array}{c|ccccccc} & A & C & ES & E& I & Alpha & Beta \\ \hline A& AwithA& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0&\\ C& 0& CwithC& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0&\\ ES& 0& 0& ESwithES& 0& 0& 0& 0&\\ E& 0& 0& 0& EwithE& 0& 0& 0& \\ I& 0& 0& 0& 0& IwithI& 0& 0& \\ Alpha& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& 1& 0& \\ Beta& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& AlphawithBeta& 1& \\ \end{array} } \right]\)
  • An F matrix indicates which variables are observed.
    • Rows with the latent variables are dropped.
    • \(F = \left[ {\begin{array}{c|ccccccc} & A & C & ES & E& I& Alpha & Beta \\ \hline A& 1& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0&\\ C& 0& 1& 0& 0& 0& 0& 0&\\ ES& 0& 0& 1& 0& 0& 0& 0&\\ E& 0& 0& 0& 1& 0& 0& 0& \\ I& 0& 0& 0& 0& 1& 0& 0& \\ \end{array} } \right]\)
  • It is essential to ensure that the variables are arranged in A, C, ES, E, and I; otherwise, the variables may be incorrectly arranged.
  • Values on the left-hand side of the labels are starting values. They usually do not affect the final results.
## Defaults: A.notation="ON", S.notation="WITH"
RAM1 <- lavaan2RAM(model1, obs.variables=c("A","C","ES","E","I"), A.notation="on", S.notation="with")

Fixed-effects TSSEM

  • Let’s see if the fixed-effects model fits the data.
  • There are two fixed-effects models implemented in the metaSEM package.
    • The multiple-group SEM approach: tssem1(Digman97.data, Digman97.n, method="FEM")
    • The random-effects model by setting \(T^2=0\): tssem1(Digman97.data, Digman97.n, method="REM", RE.type="Zero")
  • Simulation studies show that the multiple-group approach works better. However, it may not work well when there are a lot of missing data.

Stage 1 Analysis

  • Before interpreting the results, we should check the OpenMx status1 code. The optimization is okay when it is either 0 or 1.
  • The test statistic on testing the homogeneity test of the correlation matrix is \(\chi^2(df=130, N=4496)=1505.44, p < 0.001\).
  • Both the RMSEA and SRMR are very large, indicating that the proposed model (homogeneity of correlation matrices) did not fit the data well.
  • The estimates of the \(S[i,j]\) represent the element of the pooled correlation (or covariance) matrix.
## method="FEM": fixed-effects TSSEM
fixed1 <- tssem1(Digman97.data, Digman97.n, method="FEM")

## summary of the findings
summary(fixed1)

Stage 2 Analysis

  • Although the random-effects model is preferred, we illustrate how to fit the stage 2 analysis based on the fixed-effects model.
  • The proposed model appears to fit the data well with \(\chi^2(df=4, N=4,496)=65.45, p<.001, CFI=.95, RMSEA=0.06\), and \(SRMR=.03\).
  • Important notes:
    • The standard errors (SEs) of the parameter estimates are likely underestimated when the correlation matrices are not homogeneous.
    • Readers should be cautious when interpreting the results of the stage 2 analysis when the homogeneity of the correlation matrices is rejected in the stage 1 analysis.
  • Please note that the error variances are not estimated because they are not parameters when analyzing correlation matrices. We will discuss how to get them later.
fixed2 <- tssem2(fixed1, RAM=RAM1)
summary(fixed2)

Random-effects TSSEM

  • The subgroup analysis cannot help us to identify meaningful subgroups. A better option is to apply a random-effects model.

Stage 1 Analysis

  • There are ten correlation coefficients in the analysis with 55 elements in the variance component matrix of the random effects with RE.type="Symm". The OpenMx status1 is 5 indicating that there are estimation issues. We should not trust the results!
    • RE.type="Symm": \(T^2 = \left[ {\begin{array}{c|ccc} & r_{2,1} & r_{3,1} & r_{3,2}\\ \hline r_{2,1}& a& & & \\ r_{3,1}& b& d& & \\ r_{3,2}& c& e& f&\\ \end{array} } \right]\).
    • RE.type="Diag": \(T^2 = \left[ {\begin{array}{c|ccc} & r_{2,1} & r_{3,1} & r_{3,2}\\ \hline r_{2,1}& a& & & \\ r_{3,1}& 0& b& & \\ r_{3,2}& 0& 0& c&\\ \end{array} } \right]\).
    • RE.type="Zero": \(T^2 = \left[ {\begin{array}{c|ccc} & r_{2,1} & r_{3,1} & r_{3,2}\\ \hline r_{2,1}& 0& & & \\ r_{3,1}& 0& 0& & \\ r_{3,2}& 0& 0& 0&\\ \end{array} } \right]\).
## Let's try to estimate all elements in the variance component matrix RE.type="Symm".

Stage 2 Analysis

  • The stage 2 analysis is similar to that of the fixed-effects model.

  • We may trust the results based on the random-effects model.

  • The proposed model fits the data well with \(\chi^2(df=4, N=4496)=7.82, p=0.0984\), CFI=\(0.9922\), RMSEA=\(0.0146\), and SRMR=\(0.0436\).

  • The estimated correlation between the two factors (labeled AlphawithBeta in the printout) is \(0.3777\).

random2 <- tssem2(random1, RAM=RAM1)
